questions.question:
Consider the following code snippet (Java): 
class Base { int x;}
class Derived extends Base { void display() { System.out.println(x); } }
What will happen if you create an object of Derived and call display() without initializing x in Derived?

Consider the following code (C++): 
class A { public: virtual void f() { std::cout << "A"; } };
class B : public A { public: void f() override { std::cout << "B"; } };
int main() { A* a = new B(); a->f(); }
What will be the output?
